Rhode Island Department of Human Services
July 24 at 4:07 PM ·

Please share the following SNAP UPDATE regarding August 2020 Benefits. From March through July, SNAP households that weren’t already receiving the maximum SNAP benefit amount for their household size received an increase to their benefits to bring them to the maximum amount.

The federal government approved a similar increase for August 2020. On August 4, households with benefit amounts under the maximum amount will receive additional benefits as a supplement to the regular August issuance.

The amount of SNAP benefits a household receives is based on a federal formula that considers the number of people in the household as well as income and expenses. If a household’s usual benefit amount is below the maximum amount in the pictured chart below, they will receive additional benefits to bring them to the maximum amount listed for their household size.

post_text:
Falls are the number one cause of injuries in older adults, leading to broken bones, head injuries, and hospitalizations. But although the risk for falls increases as people get older, falls aren’t a normal part of aging. Join the webinar on Wednesday, July 1st at 2:00 p.m. at https://www.facebook.com/BCBSRI/ for a Strong and Balanced Flow Class.

In the class, we will practice mindfulness for fall prevention, posture correction, and a meditative approach to exercises. This class will provide ways to energize your mind and mood, unlock your joints and muscles and improve strength and balance.

Governor Raimondo announced that she will be holding an Older Adults Facebook Town Hall on Thursday, May 21 at 11:00 AM. She will be joined by Secretary Robertson, the U.S. Assistant Secretary for Aging; Secretary Womazetta Jones of the Executive Office of Health and Human Services; Office of Healthy Aging Director Rose Jones and several community advocates.

post_text:
Blue Cross & Blue Shield of Rhode Island will be continuing the virtual fitness classes this week. Stay fit, stay healthy!

MONDAYS - Balance & Strength
Enjoy a little bit of everything in this hybrid class, from ballet poses to Pilates to lower body toning. Have a chair nearby to warm up and hold poses.

TUESDAYS - Core
Improve your strength and stability by challenging your core muscles. You can use props and light weights, and modifications will be suggested for beginners.

WEDNESDAYS - Strength & Tone
Sculpt your muscles with light dumbbells, a weighted ball, and your own body weight. Don't have weights? Use canned goods and a milk jug!

THURSDAYS - Stretch & Relax
Take time for yourself with this stress-reducing class. Breathe deep and focus on exercises that promote strength and flexibility.

FRIDAYS - Cardio Dance
Feel good and get your heart rate up! This class varies between higher and lower intensity, but you can take it all at your own speed.

North Providence Mancini Center added 45 new photos — with The Village at Waterman Lake and Dominick Ruggerio at North Providence Mancini Center.
February 20 at 9:47 AM · North Providence, RI ·

We had a wonderful time at our Valentine’s Day Dine & Dance on Thursday, February 13th! Red roses were provided to all the ladies courtesy of Mayor Lombardi. Tom Conte, a Mancini Center favorite, kept us dancing all afternoon. The desserts were abundant and the smiles were wide! As always, we could not have done it without our amazing staff, volunteers and sponsors. We’d like to thank A.A. Mariani & Son, The Village at Waterman Lake, Smithfield Woods, Anchor Bay at Pocasset, Blue Cross Blue Shield of Rhode Island and Elmhurst Rehabilitation & Healthcare Center for their sponsorship and helping hands. A special ‘Thank You!’ to Mayor Charles Lombardi, RI Senate President Dominick Ruggerio, North Providence Town Council President Dino Autiello and Chief of Staff Richard Fossa for attending the event and presenting us with a grant from PepsiCo in the amount of $2,500! We are so fortunate to have such tremendous support from our town and state. It was truly a memorable day.

post_text: Over 130 of our members came ready to party at our second annual Halloween Costume Party held on Halloween day! The creativity was off the charts this year. We were fortune enough to have some great guest judges for our costume contest: Susan from Golden Crest, Vanessa from Cedar Home Health, Maxine from Right At Home and Rose & Elise from the Office Of Healthy Aging. They certainly had a difficult time deciding who the winners of each category would be. Our day was made even better by our great sponsors: Golden Crest, A.A. Mariani & Son, The Cedars, The Bridge At Cherry Hill, Oak Street Health, Heritage Hills, Smithfield Woods and Nettie's Kettle Corn. We can't thank our many wonderful volunteers enough...without them, we could never put on such a lavish event. Thank you Russell, Rita, Sandra, Diane, Robin Judy, Maria, Linda and Paulina! DJ Eddie the Fixer kept everyone dancing all afternoon. Thank you to Mayor Lombardi for taking time out of his busy day to address and mingle with everyone. Thank you also to The Valley Breeze for capturing the day for us.

Special thanks to judges Alyson Walsh of Smithfield Woods, Susan Silva of Golden Crest and Vanessa Carnevale of Cedar Home Health. Town of North Providence
July 18, 2019 at 7:23 PM ·

***URGENT MESSAGE TO NORTH PROVIDENCE RESIDENTS***
Due to the upcoming Excessive Heat Warning issued by the National Weather service for our area on Saturday, the North Providence Emergency Management Agency has activated its Cooling Center plan. If there are any North Providence residents that need cooling assistance because of the excessive heat on Saturday or Sunday they are to call the North Providence Fire Dept at 231-8500 and your name and address will be taken. Emergency Management will then contact you to give assistance. If transportation to our Cooling Center located at the Mancini Center on Atlantic Blvd is needed, the Emergency Management agency will assist you in transportation there. We ask that you check on your elderly neighbors often during this heat warning and call use with any concerns you may have about them if they live alone. Our Emergency Medical Services Chief will arrange to visit and check on their situation and insure they are safe.
